In article <CB576A.F6p@rahul.net> dhesi@rahul.net (Rahul Dhesi) writes:
>Although the difficulty of finding the 80-bit key through a brute-force
>search is of interest, of greater interest is the difficulty of finding
>the key given 40 of its bits. The key escrow scheme assumes that a
>government agency that has half of the key can do nothing useful with
>it alone.  How true is this assumption?

As I understand it, each escrow agent has 80 bits that must be combined
(probably by OR-ing together or some such) to give the key. If so, nobody
has 40 bits of the key. As you suggest, it would be much weaker if each
escrow agent had 40 bits of the real key.

David

